 of   Torrens  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in Lancashire, England."],"variants":[{"name":"Torrens","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Raul, Jaime, Jorge, Luis, Manuel, Aida, Alejandro, Ana, Andres, Anselmo, Benito, Caridad.","Catalan: altered form of <b>Torrents</b>, a topographic name for someone living by the course of a torrent, from the plural of Catalan <i>torrent</i> ‘mountain stream, torrent’ (from Latin <i>torrens</i>).","Irish (Derry and Antrim): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Toráin</b>, <b>Ó Taráin</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Torán</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of Gaelic <i>tor</i> ‘tower, champion, hero’, or possibly a borrowing of Norse <i>Thorfinn</i>, compare   Corrin  . The final extraneous or possessive <i>-s</i> (sometimes spelt <i>-ce</i>) is not original."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702079,"age":8,"year":"1520","julianDay":2276228,"title":"The Stockholm Bloodbath","description":"A mass execution of Swedish nobles by Danish king Christian II is known as the Stockholm Bloodbath. Christian II invaded Sweden in 1519 and took hold of Stockholm in September 1520. Over 80 nobles were executed for heresy on November 8 and 9. The outrage from the executions led to the Swedish removal of support of the Kalmar Union.","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Stockholm-Bloodbath","urlTitle":"Britannica - Stockholm Bloodbath","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702080,"age":11,"year":"1523","julianDay":2277324,"title":"Swedish War of Liberation","description":"The Swedish War of Liberation was a civil war led by nobleman Gustav Vasa. As Christian II heard of the rebellion, he confronted Vasa's men, who won the battle at Brunbacks Ferry. Christian II was defeated by the Swedes in Stockholm and a truce was agreed upon. Vasa was given as a hostage as a show of good faith until the treaty was signed. The Danish King did not keep his word and Vasa was held as a prisoner for two years until his escape. A bounty was placed on Vasa's head. Vasa worked to inspire many to join his cause and lived under disguise until the Danes surrendered in 1525.","url":"https://www.sweden.org.za/swedish-monarchy-gustav-vasa.html","urlTitle":"Sweden.org - Swedish Monarchy Gustav Vasa","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702086,"age":32,"year":"1544","julianDay":2284994,"title":"Sweden Becomes Lutheran Nation","description":"Sweden officially declared itself a Lutheran nation in 1544.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357053,"age":39,"year":"1551","julianDay":2287551,"description":"Sweden seized territory of Estonia.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357055,"age":105,"year":"1617","julianDay":2311658,"description":"Treaty of Stolbovo ended Swedish occupation of Northern Russia.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357056,"age":106,"year":"1618","julianDay":2312023,"description":"1618-1648 Sweden fights in the Thirty Years' War.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Jöran was born about 1512, in Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden. She married Örjan 'Göran' Jakobsson or Jåpsson about 1630, in Ytterbyn, Norrbotten, Sweden. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1512–":"umbes 1512–Surnud","1507–Male":"1507–Surnud","1533–Male":"1533–Surnud","1535–1599":"1535–1599","1537–Male":"1537–Surnud","1512–Female":"1512–Surnud","Abt 1512":"umbes 1512","abt 1533":"umbes 1533","1535":"1535","1523":"1523","1512":"1512","1544":"1544","1599":"1599","1533":"1533","abt 1537":"umbes 1537","1520":"1520","ABT 1630":"umbes 1630","1551":"1551","1618":"1618","1617":"1617","1507":"1507","1537":"1537","Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden":"Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Rootsi","Innanbäcken, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden":"Innanbäcken, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Rootsi","of Ytterbyn, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden":"Ytterbyn, Norrbotten, Rootsi","Innanbäcken,Nederkalix,Norrbotten,Sverige":"Innanbäcken, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Rootsi","Innanbäcken 3, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sverige":"Innanbäcken, Nede